defaultThough the contribution made by level crossings to overall pedestrian, cyclist
default, horse-rider 
defaultand 
defaultmotor
default vehicle user safety risk is very small, it is striking that media/public 
defaultinterest in level crossing accidents is sometimes very much greater than in equivalent incidents not involving the railways.
defaultLevel crossings also present a risk to the safety of rail passengers and on-board rail staff, as the incident at Ufton Nervet in 20
default04 demonstrated
default: the train driver and
default five rail passengers died
default. 
defaultDespite this, rail travel is around 500 times safer than cycling or walking, and 30 times safer than using a car, when measured in terms of fatalities per 
defaultmillion 
defaultkilometre
defaults 
defaulttravelled.
default It is 
defaultimportant to consider relative safety levels across the transport modes and the overall cost-effectiveness of measures when deciding on safety investment
defaults
default. 
defaultIn PACTS’ view, 
defaultthere is no room for complacency about safety 
defaultat level crossings
default. New 
defaultequipment
default, improved management techniques and 
defaultinvestment make higher safety standards possible. And expectations of greater safety on the part of the public demand further improvements. The challenge for the railway is to deliver these 
defaultat a
defaultn
default 
defaultacceptable 
defaultprice
default,
default both 
defaultin terms of the capital costs involved and (often) reduced railway efficiency and convenience for road users. 
default&#xa0;
defaultRep
defaultlacing level crossings with 
defaultroad 
defaultbridges/underpasses has economic benefits for both local communities and the railway, but the predominant benefit is on the non-railway side. 
defaultUninterrupt
defaulted road-traffic flows and reduced delays are the principal benefits on
default the “road” side. Reduced maintenance 
defaultand staff 
defaultcosts and (marginally) increased railway capacity (by eliminating train-speed restrictions necessitated by level crossings) are the principal benefits to the railways. One of the challenges we face in improvi
defaultng level crossing safety is ensuring that those who benefit make an appropriate contribution to the costs of improvements. 
defaultThe option of simply eliminating level crossings – particularly where there are already convenient alternative routes over/under the
default railway – is frequently cost-effective but can be controversial. An example was reported recently:
defaultThe Aristotle Lane footpath level crossing in Oxford has been the subject of a determined resistance to the closure of the level crossing on safety grounds.
default Despite an alternative route via a nearby over-bridge, closure of the crossing was not secured through the public inquiry into the upgrading of the Oxford-Bicester railway. Now, because Network Rail and Chiltern Railways (the principal beneficiary of the 
defaultupgrade) continue to maintain that closure is necessary on safety grounds, one of those opposed to closure has submitted a planning application for an additional track across Aristotle Lane level crossing. This is to force the planners to face up to his po
defaultint of view that planning permission is required for the works proposed by Chiltern Railways and Network Rail.(Source: LXInfo.org 2 September 2013)
defaultDespite 
defaultsuch
default challenges, Network Rail is reported
default to have closed 700 level crossings since 2009, with 11
default7 c
defaultrossings closed in 2012/13. 
defaultPACTS believes that the established rights and reasonable needs of the public and business should be properly considered when closure of a level crossing is contemplated. Closure should not be seen 
defaultas an easy option. On the whole, however, the procedures currently seem to make closure a difficult 
defaultand protracted option and local authorities which 
defaultwould
default 
defaulttend
default to err on the side of safety with respect to roads, 
defaultmay oppose closure of level crossings. 
defaultLev
defaultel crossings vary in type and the risks associated with each location may also vary. As such, a variety of methods will be required to improve safety across the network. 
defaultAnnex 1 details the various types of level crossing in use.
default 
defaultSafety risk can be reduce
defaultd by “upgrading” the crossing type from, for example, an automatic open crossing to an automatic half-barrier crossing.
default 
defaultBut “upgrading” is not necessarily cost-effective. 
defaultIt
default can be expensive, and the expense disproportionate to the risk reduction achieved.
default Reducing the costs associated with upgrading by, for example, greater standardisation 
defaultand improved project management, 
defaultwould be helpful.
defaultThe Rail Accident Investigation Branch suggests that at some locations there may be comparatively inexpensive measures
default which could improve level crossing safety. Its 2012 Annual Report
default 
defaultidentified a range of local factors that might influence (i.e. have the potential to improve) the behaviour of crossing users. These include:
default•
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultlocal obstructions to the sighting of trains;
default•
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultenvironmental conditions such as traffic noise and visibility at night;
default•
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultgates left open at user-worked crossings;
default•
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultanxiety to cross the line to catch a train (station crossings);
default•
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultvisibility of road traffic signals (e.g. impact of glare from sunlight); and
default•
default 
default              
defaultthe audibility of train horns.
default&#xa0;
defaultKnowing the specific local conditions, circumstances and user
default behaviour
default can be important. In this respect the appointment by Network Rail of dedicated level crossing managers is a welcome development. 
