default Within the context of the CP5 settleme
defaultnt, given the number of fatalities each year and the potential for catastrophic failure, PACTS feels this level of investment in level crossing safety is about right. 
defaultThe mainline railway uses sophisticated models to understand the risks it manages and to
default prioritise risk reduction. 
defaultWe would urge the Government to bear in mind the relative levels of risk across the modes in determining policy and investment levels. 
defaultBecause most accidents at level crossings result from user behaviour (such as misjudgements, errors and wilful misuse) rather than technical or engineering failures, it is not self-evident that major expenditure on technical improvements will significantly
default reduce risk. 
defaultGetting a better understandi
defaultng of the reasons for user 
defaultbehaviour is essential. The Rail Accident Investigation Branch’s (RAIB’s) continuing investigations into level crossing accidents provide a good basis for action. RAIB’s Chief Inspector 
defaulthas observed
default that the RAIB has “
defaultmade repeated recommendations concerning realistic and rigorous assessment of the risks at individual crossings; understanding the local and human factors that may influence the risk to the users, and the implementation of 
defaultimprovements identified during risk assessments and inspections. Not all our recommendations require a long lead time or significant resource. I urge both Network Rail and RSSB, who are carrying out related research on crossings, to review the resources co
defaultmmitted to this work and wherever possible ensure that the individual elements of their programmes that will address these risks are completed at the very earliest opportunity.”
defaultThe 
defaultRSSB
default has a significant research programme, funded by the Department for Tr
defaultansport, into these issues.
default 
defaultResearch published in 2011 investigated the signs, signals, markings and other road design elements that best convey the information road users need when approaching public road level crossings. 
defaultThe second phase of this research
default will be published in May 2014. 
defaultCurrent research projects 
defaultinclude one addressing the signage provided at private level crossings and another addressing the causes of pedestrian accidents at level crossings and potential solutions
default.
default 
defaultWe believe it important 
defaultthat this research is expedited and translated into practical action as soon as practicable.
defaultNetwork Rail is reported to be on course to deliver a 25% reduction level crossi
defaultng risk between 2009 and 2014.
default 
defaultWe understand that the company is committed 
defaultto achieving further risk reduction
defaults
default 
defaultafter 2014.
default 
defaultIt is apparent that 
defaultNetwork Rail
default has increased its management focus on this issue and has allocated increased resources accordingly
default. 
defaultWith so many level crossings and the inherent risks asso
defaultciat
defaulted
default with
default many of them, the test will be whether Network Rail can sustain its focus and 
defaulteffective management. 
defaultLevel crossing risk is not only a matter for Network Rail and the communities near le
defaultvel crossings on the national network. There are level crossings on heritage and light railways that require a similarly robust approach to risk management.
default&#xa0;
defaultWe have already drawn attention, in our response to question 1, to what the ORR’s annual health and safety report says about Network Rail’s management of level crossing risk. T
defaulthe report includes few details of the means by which the Regulator reached its views, and it is therefore difficult to draw conclusions about either the extent or effectiveness of its regulatory actions.
defaultThe ORR’s policy in respect of level crossings is se
defaultt out in its Railway Safety Publication 7
default. The policy says that 
defaultORR seeks to influence duty holders and others to reduce risk at Britain’s level crossings through means ranging from advice to formal enforcement action. ORR checks that preventive and 
defaultprotective measures are implemented. The ORR says that risk control should, where practicable, be achieved through eliminating level crossings in favour of bridges, underpasses or diversions. Where elimination is not possible, ORR aims to ensure that duty 
defaultholders reduce risk so far as is reasonably practicable
default. 
defaultThe ORR acknowledges its role in providing clear advice and enforcing relevant legislation – including that which relates to level crossings. The ORR exercises the powers of the Secretary of State 
defaultfor Transport in making level crossing orders under the Level Crossings Act 1983. 
defaultThe ORR takes the view that it is neither effective nor efficient for rail companies 
defaultalone 
defaultto be responsible for managing safety at level crossings. 
defaultIt
default say
defaults
default that decisions a
defaultbout level crossings should involve rail companies, traffic authorities and other relevant organisations as early on as possible. Relevant authorities should recognise the wider benefits that safety improvements at level crossings (for example, replacing t
defaulthem with bridges) can bring about, particularly for road users. If wider benefits can be achieved, the appropriate funding bodies should agree on how the costs of making safety improvements will be met. 
defaultThe ORR is also committed to helping people understa
defaultnd the importance of the safe use of level crossings. The guidance ‘Using Level Crossings Safely’ is available on ORR’s website. 
defaultWe are unaware of any 
defaultspecific 
defaultrecent statement of Government policy in respect of level crossing
default safety. It is not mentioned,
default for example, in the March 2013 Command Paper “Reforming our Railways”. W
defaulte note that the Government’s high-level output specification (HLOS) for 2014-19 allocates £67m for level crossing improvements and closures
default.
default 
defaultThough little in the context of overall Go
defaultvernment expenditure on railways, we believe it significant that 
defaultlevel crossings have been singled out for investment.
defaultThis issue has been investigated jointly by the Law Commission and the S
defaultcottish Law Commission. 
defaultThey published a
default consultation paper, containin
defaultg proposals for law reform, 
defaultin July 2010.
defaultThe provisional proposals put forward in the consultation paper represented the Commissions’ initial view about how the law should be reformed
default.
default 
defaultThe two
default Commission
defaults
default then approved the instruction of Parliamentary Counsel to prepare a draft Bill and Regulations under the Health and Safety at Work etc Act 1974, to give effect to their proposals.
defaultAccording to the Law Commission’s website, Parliamentary
default Counsel have drafted a Bill and Regulations, and the Commissions are in the final stages of drafting a report which contains detailed recommendations, together with explanatory notes for the Bill and Regulations, an analysis of the consultation responses 
defaultreceived and an economic impact assessment.
defaultOur expectation is that the Law Commissions’ report will recommend sweeping away
default and/or updating
default much, if not all, of the existing legislation governing level crossings. We hope that the revised legislative approach will encourage greater collaboration between rail and road authorities in managing level crossing risk. We are, though, concerned at the
default time that has elapsed since the Law Commissions’ consultation exercise, and trust that their final report will emerge very soon.
defaultNetwork Rail has done much to publicise the risks 
defaultassociated with level crossings.
default 
defaultIn addition to television advertisements, they have provided educational resources for use in both primary and secondary schools, and are currently running a campaign aimed at young people.
default 
defaultWe understand that analysis of N
defaultetwork Rail’s television campaigns showed that they were successful in increasing public awareness of the issue.
default 
defaultAssessing the effectiveness of such campaigns
default is much harder.
default 
defaultWe know of no clear evidence on the extent to which increased public awareness of
default a safety issue results in changed behaviour or improved safety.
default 
defaultWe suggest that the Network Rail work with the road safety professionals in DfT, including the THINK! team, in local authorities, the emergency services and elsewhere, who have experience of
default road user safety campaigns. Many of the messages and techniques relevant to level crossing safety will be applicable to road safety. These other authorities must share the responsibility for level crossing safety, even if the expenditure comes from Networ
defaultk Rail. 
defaultThe mechanisms by which Network Rail, and other railway operators, become aware of land-use changes in the vicinity of level crossings need to be robust. Planning authorities need to recognise circumstances where new developments might increase pe
defaultdestrian, cycle or road vehicle use of level crossings, and take steps to alert the railway companies involved. 
